{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418512"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"297"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:03:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"297"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261521","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261521"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:36:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:37:56+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":5,"questionsAnswered":5,"marksTotal":5,"marksAttainable":5,"marksAttempted":5,"finishedAt":null,"resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.4,"questionsCorrect":2,"marksCorrect":2},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/297"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.48,0.12,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90690"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/297"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"297"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74861"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"315"},{"type":"tags","id":"951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8851"},{"type":"tags","id":"9485"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31098"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42049"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44918"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90690"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of weakness in the left side of his face. He has also noticed a lump in front of his left ear that has been slowly growing over the past few months. His medical history includes hypertension for which he takes perindopril. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals loss of motor function across the entire left side of his face, including inability to raise his eyebrows and loss of the left nasolabial fold. A firm, non-tender 3 cm mass is palpable anterior to his left tragus. The remainder of his neurological and general examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Carotid artery ultrasound","Mumps serology","MRI of the head and neck","Varicella zoster serology","CT scan of the head without contrast"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a lower motor neuron facial nerve palsy in association with a parotid mass, which is highly concerning for a malignant parotid tumour with facial nerve involvement. The facial nerve (cranial nerve VII) runs through the parotid gland, making it vulnerable to compression or invasion by parotid tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI of the head and neck\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation in this scenario. MRI provides superior soft tissue contrast compared to CT and better delineates the relationship between the parotid mass and the facial nerve. It can help determine the extent of the tumour, potential perineural spread, and involvement of adjacent structures, which are crucial for surgical planning and prognostication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the head without contrast\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide optimal visualisation of the soft tissue structures of the parotid gland and would be inadequate for evaluating the facial nerve. If CT were to be used, it would need to include contrast enhancement and focus on the parotid region rather than just the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid artery ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was concern for a cerebrovascular event. However, the pattern of facial weakness in this case is consistent with a lower motor neuron lesion (affecting the entire side of the face including the forehead), rather than an upper motor neuron lesion (which typically spares the forehead). Additionally, the presence of a parotid mass makes a vascular cause less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMumps serology\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if acute parotitis was suspected. However, mumps typically causes painful parotid swelling, often bilateral, and is unlikely to cause facial nerve palsy. The chronic nature of the mass and the absence of pain or systemic symptoms make mumps highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster serology\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered if Ramsay Hunt syndrome (herpes zoster oticus) was suspected. However, this condition typically presents with a painful vesicular rash in the ear canal or auricle, which is not described in this case. The presence of a parotid mass also makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing imaging, fine needle aspiration or core biopsy of the mass would likely be the next step to establish a tissue diagnosis. Management would depend on the histology but typically involves surgical resection with potential adjuvant radiotherapy for malignant tumours.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Facial weakness with a parotid mass is highly suggestive of a malignant parotid tumour with facial nerve involvement.","Lower motor neuron facial palsy affects the entire side of the face including the forehead, unlike upper motor neuron lesions which spare the forehead.","MRI provides superior soft tissue contrast and is the preferred imaging modality for evaluating parotid masses and facial nerve involvement."],"references":["Laurie S. Salivary gland tumors: Epidemiology, diagnosis, evaluation, and staging. In: Brockstein BE, Brizel DM, Fried MP editors.;\u200bUpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021. [updated 2021 Feb 04; cited 2021 Apr 19]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/salivary-gland-tumors-epidemiology-diagnosis-evaluation-and-staging","Wierzbicka M, Kope\u0107 T, Szyfter W, Kereiakes T, Bem G. The presence of facial nerve weakness on diagnosis of a parotid gland malignant process. Eur Arch Otorhinolaryngol. 2012 Apr;269(4):1177-82. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3311986/#Sec5","Kim SY, Boner U, LeeJ-H, et al.Magnetic resonance imaging of parotid gland tumors: a pictorial essay  BMC Med Imaging. 2022; 22:191.  doi: 10.1186/s12880-022-00924-0."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74861"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"297"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74861"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:08:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T15:08:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"297"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90690"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":